title: For Sale:  DELUXE REMINGTON-KEENE BOLT ACTION SPORTING RIFLE
postcontent: Very rare Special Order Deluxe Remington-Keene Sporting Rifle, 40-60 Marlin Caliber, 24 & 1/2 inch Half Octagon Barrel, Fancy Walnut Stock, Extra Fine Checkering, Pistol Grip, Plain Front Sight, Combination Open and Peep Rear Sight, Case Hardened Cocking Lever, and Buttplate with a Trapdoor, with a Cleaning Rod Cavity in the stock. No visible serial number on the exterior surface, however, a three digit number is stamped inside the trapdoor of the buttplate. In my estimation, which is inline with a professional appraisal, this rifle is all original, with the possible exception that the hammer fly might or might not have been removed at the factory, enabling the rifle to come to a full-cock upon each cycle of the bolt, like that of the Model 1878 Experimental Rifle, rather than half-cock like that of the Model 1880. Condition in my opinion is NRA Antique Fine to Excellent considering that the hammer fly might have been removed at the factory. The action is strong and very smooth. The screw heads are mostly perfect with but a few showing evidence of the slightest use. In my estimation, the metal finish ranges in quality from a bright blue to a rich patina mix of varying shades, coupled with scattered light freckling mostly on the octagon part of the barrel with some on the hammer. The hammer retains most of its case colors. The trapdoor of the buttplate automatically snaps shut upon attempting to close it manually. The wood finish also shows the lightest of scattered handling marks. There is a very thin crack in the wood that starts at the rear of the upper tang and curls about 5/8ths of an inch to the edge of the checkering as pictured. The crack is possibly due to the over tightening of the tang screw, and it gives every appearance of being superficial and insignificant when it comes to the extra solid wood to metal fit and function of the rifle. Bore: Excellent. All in all, this is a very rare and well cared for special order rifle according to its features and the information contained in reference material including Remington catalogs.
